subtitles.text: Tonight, we're putting celebrities under huge amounts of pressure and strain
in the hope that one of them cracks.
Is it fair on them? No.
Is it fun for me? You betcha.
This is The Weakest Link.
Behind me are eight famous faces
wondering if this might be the last they ever see of their dignity.
They're each trying to win up to £50,000 for charity -
but to do that, they'll have to work together.
Seven will leave with nothing,
as round by round, we lose the player voted the weakest link.
Let's meet the team.
I'm Mel B, I'm a Spice Girl, a women's rights campaigner,
and I'm from Leeds.
I'm Nick, I play Tony in TV's Hollyoaks and I'm from London.
I'm Robert, a carpenter expert on the show Sort Your Life Out,
and I'm from north-west London.
I'm Arielle, I'm a DJ and presenter on Radio 1, and I'm from Glasgow.
I'm Shobna, I'm an actor and an author,
and I'm from Lancashire.
I'm Eamonn, I'm a broadcaster, and I'm from Belfast.
I'm Denis, I'm an actor,
I'm from Crieff in Perthshire.
I'm Briony, I'm a TV chef and Great British Bake Off
semifinalist from Bristol.
Fantastic intros, guys, huh?
Feel the energy in the room, huh?
What you're feeling right now is pure buzz.
I'm very excited for you.
OK, here are the rules.
In each round, the aim is to answer enough questions correctly
to reach your target within the time limit.
The target for round one is £2,500.
The fastest way to get there is to work together
to create a chain of eight correct answers.
Get your question wrong,
you break the chain
and you lose all of the money in that chain -
but if you press your button
and say bank before the question is asked,
the money is safe and you begin a new chain from scratch.
You've got two minutes and 30 seconds for this round,
and we'll start with the person most likely
to preface whatever part of the country they're in
with the word "sunny".
That's you, Eamonn Holmes.
Thank you very much. You're very welcome.
Let's play The Weakest Link.
Start the clock.
In fairy tales, which character who loses a shoe
in the rush to leave a ball by midnight,
has a name that relates to the ashes found in a fireplace?
Cinderella. Correct. Denis.
In leisure, a large circular ring
that can be spun around the waist, limbs or neck by rotating the body
has what two-word name?
Hula hoop. Correct. Briony.
In food, people from Devon and Cornwall disagree
about the order that jam and cream should be served
on which baked product?
Scones. Correct. Bank. Mel B.
In technology, the social media platform Twitter was rebranded
in 2023 to become known by what single-letter name?
X. Correct. Nick.
In transport, the reflective road studs invented by Percy Shaw
to distinguish traffic lanes have what name,
pig's ears or cat's eyes?
Cat's eyes. Correct. Robert.
What consumer magazine
that independently reviews products and services
sounds like the name for a woman with supernatural powers
who rides on a broomstick?
Which? Correct. Bank. Arielle.

without seeing the face of their prospective soulmate
is titled Love Is what?
Blind. Correct.
Shobna. Bank. In the military,
what T comes before "army" in the former name
of the volunteer force that has been renamed Army Reserve?
Territorial. Correct. Eamonn.
In sport, what is the name of the object
traditionally made with cork and feathers
that is struck with racquets in a game of badminton?
Shuttlecock. Correct.
Denis. Look at your screen.
This is a still from which 1996 film?
Sorry. No. Mission: Impossible. Briony.
In space, the type of huge black hole
found at the centre of most large galaxies
are described as what? Mega bulky or super massive?
Super massive. Correct.
Mel B, given to civilians for their service or achievements,
the title Member of the Order of the British Empire
is commonly known by what three-letter abbreviation?
MBE. Correct. Nick.
In business, the alliterative term for a product sold cheaply
with no profit in order to attract customers is a loss what?
Sale. Leader.
Robert.
In pastimes, the extra playing card in a standard pack
that usually features an image of a jester has what name?
Joker. Correct.
Arielle. In religion, according to legend,
which patron saint drove the snakes out of Ireland?
Um...
St Patrick. Correct.
Shobna. In fashion, in the name of a type of fragrance,
the abbreviation EDT stands for "eau de" what?
Toilette. Correct. Eamonn.
In expressions, the phrase "par for the course"
comes from a suggested performance target in which sport?
Golf. Correct. Denis.
In the human body, what F is the name for any digit of the hand?
The correct answer is finger.
Celebrities, I can tell you that you banked £550
out of a possible £2,500.
That's exactly the reaction that deserves.
LAUGHTER
If I was still a teacher, I'd give that sort of a C minus
and tell you to concentrate a bit more.
So, who thinks Prosecco is the opposite of Conseco?
Who thinks the pie chart is the menu in Greggs?
One of you is about to leave with nothing.
It's time to vote off the weakest link.
Well, at least the team are off the mark
with some money banked.
There were lots of correct answers in the round,
and the only slip-ups came from Denis and Nick.
How will this first vote play out?

Nick.

Denis.
Denis.

So, Nick, it's over.
Uh, Nick, you OK?
Yeah. My mum will be really upset.

but with four votes, you are the weakest link.
Goodbye. Thank you.

isn't it, really? There's nothing you can do about it,
and just get the early train home.

Denis.
Denis.
Denis.
Denis.

Denis.
